<div class="post-161 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-uncategorized fpost" id="post-161">
				
				
					
						<div class="post-meta fix">	
							
							<div class="post-header fix post-nothumb" style="" >
																<div class="post-title-section fix">

									<div class="post-title fix">
										<h2>
											<a href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=161" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Central American shamans and philosophies II">Central American shamans and philosophies II</a>
										</h2>
																				<div class="metabar">
											<em>
												
																								<span class="sword">by</span> <span class="post-author vcard"><a href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?author=1">Veleda</a></span>

																								
																									<span class="sword">on</span> <abbr title="2011-04-24" class="published">April 24, 2011</abbr>
																								
																								&middot;												<a rel="nofollow" class="comments-num" href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=161#comments" title="View Comments">No Comments</a>
																								
																								
																																			</em>
										</div>
									</div>


								</div>
																		<div class="post-excerpt">
											<p>Continuing with excerpts from Brinton&#8217;s 1989 Nagualism (see previous post) with my comments in italics As is nearly always the case, the shamans are described in negative and demonized terms. Even so, the outlines of the description below correspond to shamanic healing methods. The learned historian, Orozco y Berra, speaks of the powers attributed at [...]</p>
										</div>

