									<div class="post-title fix">
										<h2>
											<a href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=152" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Coamizagual and Central American shamans">Coamizagual and Central American shamans</a>
										</h2>
																				<div class="metabar">
											<em>
												
																								<span class="sword">by</span> <span class="post-author vcard"><a href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?author=1">Veleda</a></span>

																								
																									<span class="sword">on</span> <abbr title="2011-04-24" class="published">April 24, 2011</abbr>
																								
																								&middot;												<a rel="nofollow" class="comments-num" href="http://www.sourcememory.net/veleda/?p=152#comments" title="View Comments">3 Comments</a>
																								
																								
																																			</em>
										</div>
									</div>


								</div>
																		<div class="post-excerpt">
											<p>I&#8217;m going to share some information from an old book which is a rich source on Mexican and Central American shamans and their cosmologies: Daniel G. Brinton, Nagualism. A Study Of Native American Folk-Lore And History. Philadelphia: Maccalla &amp; Company, 1894. The language, while Victorian and somewhat romanticized in places, is less racist and sexist [...]</p>
										</div>

